04818nam a22007215i 9780226534916DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017041483  a9780226534916  a(DE-B1597)523795  a(OCoLC)1029200485  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aGN21.D37bV37 2018 4aGN21.D37bV37 2018eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a301.0922231 aVarel, David A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lost Black Scholar :bResurrecting Allison Davis in American Social Thought /cDavid A. Varel. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b16 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Coming of Age during Jim Crow -- t2. Harlem from Hampton -- t3. The Making of a Social Anthropologist -- t4. Into the Southern “Wilds” -- t5. Caste, Class, and Personality -- t6. Bending the Academic Color Line -- t7. Critiquing Middle-Class Culture -- t8. Rethinking Intelligence -- t9. From Brown v. Board to Head Start -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tArchival Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAllison Davis (1902–83), a preeminent black scholar and social science pioneer, is perhaps best known for his groundbreaking investigations into inequality, Jim Crow America, and the cultural biases of intelligence testing. Davis, one of America’s first black anthropologists and the first tenured African American professor at a predominantly white university, produced work that had tangible and lasting effects on public policy, including contributions to Brown v. Board of Education, the federal Head Start program, and school testing practices. Yet Davis remains largely absent from the historical record. For someone who generated such an extensive body of work this marginalization is particularly surprising. But it is also revelatory. In The Lost Black Scholar, David A. Varel tells Davis’s compelling story, showing how a combination of institutional racism, disciplinary eclecticism, and iconoclastic thinking effectively sidelined him as an intellectual. A close look at Davis’s career sheds light not only on the racial politics of the academy but also the costs of being an innovator outside of the mainstream. Equally important, Varel argues that Davis exemplifies how black scholars led the way in advancing American social thought. Even though he was rarely acknowledged for it, Davis refuted scientific racism and laid bare the environmental roots of human difference more deftly than most of his white peers, by pushing social science in bold new directions. Varel shows how Davis effectively helped to lay the groundwork for the civil rights movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican American anthropologistsvBiography. 0aAfrican American anthropologists-Biography. 0aAfrican American college teachersvBiography. 0aAfrican American college teachers-Biography. 0aAfrican American educatorsvBiography. 0aAfrican American educators-Biography. 0aAfrican American scholarsvBiography. 0aAfrican American scholars-Biography. 0aDavis, Allison,-1902-1983. 0aUniversity of Chicago-Biography. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBrown v. Board of Education.  aHead Start.  aJim Crow.  aUniversity of Chicago.  acivil rights movement.  aclass.  ainequality.  aintelligence testing.  arace.  aracism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226534916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226534916/original  a9